{# ── Mobile-accordion / desktop-open sync ──
   Modern browsers (Chrome 132+ for example) implement `<details>` with
   an internal ::details-content pseudo that uses `content-visibility:
   hidden` when [open] isn't set — which can't be overridden via the
   children's CSS. So forcing the content visible on desktop via
   `display: block !important` doesn't actually work in those browsers
   (the wrapping pseudo is still hidden, collapsing the <ul> to 0 px).

   Reliable fix: add the `[open]` attribute itself on desktop, remove
   it on mobile. Keeps native <details> mechanics intact in both modes.
   The matchMedia listener re-syncs on resize so the user gets correct
   behavior whether they load on desktop and resize down, or vice
   versa. Idempotent — running multiple times is safe.

   The initial sync is deferred via requestAnimationFrame so the
   querySelectorAll + setAttribute work happens AFTER the browser's
   first paint commit, eliminating the synchronous forced-reflow
   that Lighthouse attributed ~270 ms of TBT to. #}
<script>
  (function () {
    var mq = window.matchMedia('(min-width: 768px)');
    var sync = function () {
      var details = document.querySelectorAll(
        '.site-footer details.footer-group--collapsible'
      );
      if (!details.length) return;
      var setOpen = mq.matches;
      // Batch attribute mutations inside rAF — keeps them out of the
      // current frame's layout, avoiding forced-reflow attribution.
      requestAnimationFrame(function () {
        for (var i = 0; i < details.length; i++) {
          if (setOpen) details[i].setAttribute('open', '');
          else details[i].removeAttribute('open');
        }
      });
    };
    sync();
    if (mq.addEventListener) mq.addEventListener('change', sync);
    else if (mq.addListener) mq.addListener(sync);
  })();
</script>
